english:
  title: Preface to Poems Sent Off to Cao Taixu Upon His Departure for the Capital
  author: Hong Gwidae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On the third day of the seventh autumn month—the Great Birthday of our Son of Heaven—in the eleventh year of the Hongzhi reign, our Prince selected from the court officials those refined in propriety and reverent in spirit, and appointed Cao Hou Taixu as emissary bearing congratulations to the throne. As he prepared to depart, someone asked the Master of Clear Contemplation: "If one has already climbed the heights of Mount Tai, why climb mountains again? If one has beheld the vastness of the boundless sea, why gaze upon water anew? If one's breast contains the breadth of heaven and earth, why undertake distant journeys?

    "Consider one whose vessel is so expansive, whose understanding so profound, whose writings so rich and lustrous as Cao Hou—even without stepping beyond his threshold, he already encompasses the majesty of Tai and the depths of the ocean, the vastness of the Nine Provinces and the Four Seas. What need has he for the rhapsodies of Qu Yuan or the travels of Sima Qian?"

    I replied: "Alas, this is not so. The Way of the gentleman extends from the nearest span to the uttermost reaches of heaven and earth. In smallness it has no interior, in greatness no exterior—such things cannot be measured by shallow understanding or idle hearsay.

    "All know that Cao Hou's vessel is already vast beyond measure. Yet his aspirations are otherwise. He never ceases his advance. In letters, he accepts nothing below the Three Dynasties and Two Hans. In governance, his standards are Gao Yao, Kui, and Ji—lesser men he scarce deems worthy of mention. He sets his sights on ruling like Yao and Shun; the Five Hegemons he regards with shame. Such a man does not stop until he has reached his goal, does not rest until death claims him. How could he confine himself to one corner, content to sit in a well?

    "Moreover, our Prince serves the greater realm with utmost sincerity, and the Ming court has shown him extraordinary favor. How could we entrust an ordinary envoy with the embassy? Could Cao Hou refuse to go?

    "Yan-jing is the ancient domain of Ji Province, the former capital of Yao and Shun. The ritual propriety and cultural refinement of the Ming surpass all previous dynasties. Even now the spirit of harmonious accord between ruler and minister lingers in human intercourse—one might encounter the peers of Kui, Long, and the Eight Worthy Ones. Compared to the careful steps of Spring and Autumn ministers entering Zhou's court, what measure of gain is greater or lesser?

    "The Golden Terrace of King Zhao of Yan, the Stone Drums of King Xuan of Zhou, the towering brilliance of Changlie's prose, the pure wind of Guzhu—all these he shall contemplate and admire. Even the Bridge of An Lushan and the Marble Tower of Ding Lingwei shall stir his heart with the pathos of antiquity, moved by his nature to verse and song. What treasures might he not gather?

    "Returning eastward with such riches, he shall have much to report to his sovereign and restore the harmonious songs between ruler and minister, realizing anew the golden age of Yao and Shun. All depends on this journey. Why then would you be unwilling to go?"

    Someone laughed and said, "Your words are true!" And so we raised our cups to him in farewell, and I have recorded this conversation as a preface to his poems.
  footnotes:
    - Qu Yuan's "Far Wandering"—the poet of ancient times, finding no acceptance in his state, composed this rhapsody imagining himself traveling distant lands with immortals.
    - Sima Qian of the Han dynasty famously traveled the realm in his youth to broaden his understanding, beginning at age twenty.
    - The ancient capital of Yan-jing corresponds to present-day Beijing, in the territory historically called Ji Province in classical Chinese geography.
    - The Golden Terrace built by King Zhao of Yan to attract worthy men; it still stands near Beijing.
    - Han Yu of the Tang, known as the sage of Changlie, was so revered for his learning and prose that men regarded him as towering as Mount Tai and bright as the Northern Dipper.
